        <sharedstimulus id="assets/d67a0fbc63967cd76d4bb/passage NEW.xml">
            <label key="5d938f85702c02d662aceec507fa75bc">
                <text>Aquifers</text>
            </label>
            <label key="1514715c165506e008b66db14594d5cc">
                <text>Some of the rain that falls on land evaporates, some is carried to the oceans by rivers, and the rest drains into the soil. The water draining into the soil accumulates in the spaces within deeper rock and soil layers.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="ac1e70f0987bf705038c8109e40a12f7">
                <text>An aquifer is a layer of rock or soil that has enough spaces (porosity) to contain large amounts of water, and has sufficient connections between those spaces to allow the water to seep or flow through it (permeability). The water may eventually flow into springs, rivers or wells.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="198869cf288b213311abd5fc22016b20">
                <text>An impermeable layer of rock material, which does not allow water to pass through it, is often located below the aquifer.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="40de1eaec97feedce2568384b4347ae9">
                <text>A well is a hole drilled down from the surface into the ground to access water contained in an aquifer.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="61a67182037eb52a10a5ebfcad8aa99a">
                <text>porous spaces filled with water and air</text>
            </label>
            <label key="5a37f97a42dac8b7e85353fd6f86109e">
                <text>underground water level</text>
            </label>
            <label key="6e01594ec8f3715b9448e15e36c013a3">
                <text>aquifer layer</text>
            </label>
            <label key="22d2f4e21de7b527c25f4ebea4f733d0">
                <text>all porous spaces filled with water</text>
            </label>
        </sharedstimulus>
    </sharedstimuli>
